# Cursor rules for PalLLM

PalLLM uses the universal `AGENTS.md` convention as the source
of truth for AI / coding-agent guidance. This file points at it
so Cursor's per-repo rules pick up the same briefing every other
agent sees.

**Read AGENTS.md first.** Everything below is a TL;DR.

## Project facts (verify via `pal.ps1`)

- .NET 10 LTS, ASP.NET Core minimal APIs, NUnit 3.x, Lua 5.1
- 1315 tests, 16 / 16 drift gates, 0 build warnings
- 57 `/api/*` routes, 38 MCP tools, 19 deterministic fallback
  strategies, 122 feature-catalog entries, 6 ADRs

## Run loop

```powershell
pwsh ./pal.ps1 build      # quick build check
pwsh ./pal.ps1 test       # 1315 / 1315 expected
pwsh ./pal.ps1 audit      # 16 drift gates -- fail = stop
```

## What to NOT change without an ADR

- The portable adapter seam in
  `src/PalLLM.Domain/Portable/PortableAdapterContracts.cs`
  (ADR 0002).
- The deterministic-first reply contract - every chat must
  return a working reply even with inference off (ADR 0001).
- The bridge protocol - sidecar never reaches into Palworld
  (ADR 0003).
- Default-off opt-in posture - never flip a network-emitting
  feature to default-on (ADR 0006).

## When in doubt

- `docs/ANTI_PATTERNS.md` - what's been considered and rejected
- `docs/COOKBOOK.md` - recipes for adding endpoints / advisors
  / fallbacks / MCP tools / config flags
- `docs/EXTENSION_POINTS.md` - "where does the change go?" map
- `docs/CHEAT_SHEET.md` - one-page summary of everything
